[!TIP] Receptor location mnemonics:
All post ganglionic neurons have nicotinic receptors.
All parasympathetic effectors have muscarinic receptors.
Sweat glands (which are sympathetic) also have muscarinic receptors.

  • Hypocalcemia, Hypokalemia, Hypomagnesemia
  • Many drugs: Amiodarone, may antibiotics, Metoclopramide
  • Myocardial disease - MI, RF, III HB, cardiomyopathy

Bundle branch blocks

Left Bundle branch block

  • New onset LBBB is always pathological
  • Diagnosis of MI in patients with prexisting LBBB is difficult. (Why? )

Causes of LBBB:

  • MI
  • Hypertension
  • Aortic stenosis
  • Cardiomyopathy
  • Idiopathic fibrosis, digoxin toxicity, hyperkalemia

Right Bundle branch block

[!INFO] ECG lead placement


V6 - mid axillary
V5 - ant. axillary
V4 - Mid clavicular

$$ Therapeutic; index = \frac{LD_{50}}{ED_{50}} $$

  • Especially hypokalemia or hypomagnesemia can potentiate toxicity.
  • Hypercalcemia can increase risk of toxicity. Hypocalcemia can nullify digoxin effects. -> maintain normal electrolyte levels.
    Acute toxicity is uncommon: Effects are
  • hypomagnesemia,
  • hypoxia will predispose to exagerrated action of digoxin. - Correct before administration.
